  //   Since a+p-1 >= m+(p-1)/2 (roughly) and m >= cl: a+p-1 >= cl+(p-1)/2 >= cl+(cr-cl+2d)/2 (since (p-1)/2 > (cr-cl+2d)/2).
  //   Hmm, let's just check: a+p-1 <= fr = cr+d. And cr+1 <= cr+d iff d >= 1.
  //   If d = 0: cr+1 > cr = fr. So cr+1 is NOT in P (a+p-1 <= cr < cr+1).
  //     Then P doesn't cover cr+1. P's right end is at most cr.
  //     P's left end a < cl. So P = s[a..a+p] with a < cl and a+p-1 <= cr.
  //     p = a+p-1-a+1 = a+p-a <= cr-a+1 <= cr-0+1... hmm but a could be negative? No, a >= 0.
