  //     But p can be at most cr - 0 + 1 = cr + 1 (if a = 0).
  //     And p > cr - cl + 1. So p in (cr-cl+1, cr+1].
  //     Now P = s[a..a+p] palindrome with m = a+p/2 in [cl..cr].
  //     The right side of P ends at a+p-1. Left at a.
  //     Since P doesn't reach cr+1: a+p-1 <= cr. So the right half of P is within the run.
  //     P palindrome maps position a to a+p-1 (both endpoints). s[a] = s[a+p-1].
  //     a+p-1 in [cl..cr] (since a+p-1 <= cr and a+p-1 >= a+p-1 >= cl... is a+p-1 >= cl?
  //     m = a+p/2 >= cl. a+p-1 >= a+p/2+(p/2-1) >= cl+(p/2-1). If p >= 2: a+p-1 >= cl. Yes.)
  //     So s[a+p-1] = c. Therefore s[a] = c.
  //     Position a+1: from P palindrome s[a+1] = s[a+p-2]. If a+p-2 in [cl..cr]: s[a+p-2] = c.
  //     a+p-2 >= cl iff a+p >= cl+2. Since p > cr-cl+1 >= 1 and a >= 0: a+p > cr-cl+1 >= cl-cl+1 = 1... hmm.
  //     If cl = 1, a = 0, p = 2: a+p-2 = 0 < 1 = cl. Not in run.
  //
  //     This is case-specific and hard to generalize. Let me try yet another approach.

  // OK, I realize this extends-only-left case is also complex. Let me try assuming it's impossible
  // and see if Dafny can verify.

  // Actually, for the extends-only-left case, consider: P's right end is at a+p-1 <= fr.
  // P's midpoint m in [cl..cr]. P's right half extends (p-1)/2 (odd) or p/2-1 (even) from m.
  // For odd p: right end = m + (p-1)/2. m + (p-1)/2 <= fr = cr + d.
  //   (p-1)/2 <= cr + d - m. p <= 2(cr+d-m)+1.
  //   Also p > cr-cl+1+2d.
  //   So 2(cr+d-m)+1 > cr-cl+1+2d iff 2cr+2d-2m > cr-cl+2d iff cr-2m > -cl iff cr+cl > 2m iff m < (cl+cr)/2.
  //   Hmm, actually: 2(cr+d-m)+1 >= p > cr-cl+1+2d means 2cr+2d-2m+1 > cr-cl+1+2d.
  //   Simplify: 2cr-2m > cr-cl, i.e., cr+cl > 2m, i.e., m < (cl+cr)/2 (with integer arithmetic: m <= (cl+cr-1)/2).
  //   So the extends-only-left case requires m < (cl+cr)/2 (m is in the left half of the run).

  // For even p: right end = m + p/2 - 1. m + p/2 - 1 <= fr = cr + d.
  //   p/2 <= cr+d-m+1. p <= 2(cr+d-m+1) = 2(cr+d-m)+2.
  //   p > cr-cl+1+2d. So 2(cr+d-m)+2 > cr-cl+1+2d, same as 2cr-2m+2 > cr-cl+1, cr-2m+cl > -1, m <= (cl+cr)/2.

  // So m <= (cl+cr)/2 in the left-only case.

  // Now from the run-end condition: cr == |s|-1 || s[cr+1] != c.
  // And from P palindrome: at position m + (cr-m+1) = cr+1 (IF cr+1 is in P).
  // Is cr+1 in P? a+p-1 >= cr+1 iff a+p >= cr+2.
  //   a = m-p/2. a+p = m+p-p/2 = m+ceil(p/2).
  //   m+ceil(p/2) >= cr+2 iff ceil(p/2) >= cr-m+2.
  //   p > cr-cl+1+2d >= cr-cl+1. ceil(p/2) >= ceil((cr-cl+2)/2) = (cr-cl+2+1)/2 for odd... hmm.
  //   ceil(p/2) >= (p+1)/2 > (cr-cl+1)/2 + 1/2 = (cr-cl+2)/2. So ceil(p/2) >= (cr-cl)/2 + 1.
  //   cr-m+2: since m <= (cl+cr)/2: cr-m >= cr-(cl+cr)/2 = (cr-cl)/2.
  //   So cr-m+2 >= (cr-cl)/2+2. And ceil(p/2) >= (cr-cl)/2+1. Not >= (cr-cl)/2+2 in general.
  //   So cr+1 might NOT be in P. (It's in P only if a+p-1 >= cr+1.)

  // If cr+1 IS in P: s[cr+1] = s[a+p-1-(cr+1-a)] = s[2a+p-cr-2].
  //   2a+p-cr-2 = 2m+(p%2)-cr-2. This might be in the run, giving s[cr+1] = c.
  //   But s[cr+1] != c (unless cr = |s|-1). Contradiction!

  // If cr+1 is NOT in P: a+p-1 < cr+1, i.e., a+p-1 <= cr.
  //   Then P is entirely within [0..cr], not reaching cr+1.
  //   But P extends left: a < cl-d. And right end: a+p-1 <= cr.
  //   p <= cr - a + 1. Since a >= 0: p <= cr + 1.
  //   And p > cr - cl + 1 + 2d.
  //   So cr + 1 > cr - cl + 1 + 2d, i.e., cl > 2d. So cl >= 2d+1.
  //
  //   Also m = a + p/2 <= (a + a+p-1)/2 + 1/2 (midpoint of P).
  //   m in [cl..cr]. P palindrome: for any position x in [cl..cr] that's in P:
  //     s[x] = c (since x is in the run).
  //     Mirror in P: s[a+p-1-(x-a)] = s[2a+p-1-x] = c.
  //     2a+p-1-x: when x = cl: 2a+p-1-cl. When x = cr: 2a+p-1-cr.
  //   So s[2a+p-1-x] = c for x in [cl..min(cr, a+p-1)].
  //   These mirror positions: [2a+p-1-min(cr,a+p-1)..2a+p-1-cl].
  //   = [max(a, 2a+p-1-cr)..2a+p-1-cl].
  //   If a+p-1 <= cr: = [a..2a+p-1-cl].
  //     2a+p-1-cl = 2m+(p%2)-1-cl. Since m >= cl: >= 2cl-1-cl+0 = cl-1.
